The monarchy of the United Kingdom , commonly referred to as the British monarchy , is the form of government used by the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) by which a [hereditary monarch](/Hereditary_monarch) reigns as the [head of state](/Head_of_state), with their powers [regulated](/Constitutional_monarchy) by the [British constitution](/British_constitution). The term may also refer to the role of the [royal family](/British_royal_family) within the [UK's broader political structure](/Politics_of_the_United_Kingdom). The monarch since 8 September 2022 is King [Charles III](/Charles_III), who ascended the throne on [the death](/Death_and_state_funeral_of_Elizabeth_II) of Queen [Elizabeth II](/Elizabeth_II), his mother.  

The monarch and [their immediate family](/British_royal_family) undertake various official, ceremonial, diplomatic and representational duties. Although formally the monarch has authority over the [government](/Government_of_the_United_Kingdom)—which is known as "[His/Her Majesty's Government](/His_Majesty%27s_Government_(term))"—this power may only be used according to laws enacted in [Parliament](/Parliament_of_the_United_Kingdom) and within constraints of convention and [precedent](/Precedent). In practice the monarch's role, including that of [Head of the Armed Forces](/Head_of_the_Armed_Forces), is limited to functions such as bestowing [honours](/Orders,_decorations,_and_medals_of_the_United_Kingdom) and [appointing](/Kissing_hands) the [prime minister](/Prime_Minister_of_the_United_Kingdom), which are performed in a non‑partisan manner. &#91;a&#93; The UK Government has called the monarchy "a unique soft power and diplomatic asset". &#91;2&#93; [The Crown](/The_Crown) also occupies a unique cultural role, serving as an unofficial [brand ambassador](/Brand_ambassador) for British interests and values abroad, increasing tourism at home, and promoting charities throughout [civil society](/Civil_society). &#91;3&#93; &#91;4&#93;  

The British monarchy traces its origins from the [petty kingdoms](/Petty_kingdom) of [Anglo‑Saxon England](/Anglo-Saxon_England) and [early medieval Scotland](/Early_medieval_Scotland), which had consolidated into the separate kingdoms of [England](/Kingdom_of_England) and [Scotland](/Kingdom_of_Scotland) by the 10th century. England was [conquered by the Normans](/Norman_Conquest) in 1066, after which [Wales](/Wales) also gradually came under the control of [Anglo‑Normans](/Anglo‑Normans). The process was completed in the 13th century when the [Principality of Wales](/Principality_of_Wales) became a [client state](/Client_state) of the English kingdom. The Anglo‑Normans also established the [Lordship of Ireland](/Lordship_of_Ireland). Meanwhile, [Magna Carta](/Magna_Carta) began the process of reducing the English monarch's political powers. In the 16th century, English and Scottish monarchs played a central role in what became the religious [English Reformation](/English_Reformation) and [Scottish Reformation](/Scottish_Reformation), and the English king became [King of Ireland](/King_of_Ireland). Beginning in 1603, the English and Scottish kingdoms were ruled by a [single sovereign](/Union_of_the_Crowns) when the Scottish King James VI acceded to the throne of England as James I. From 1649 to 1660, the tradition of monarchy was broken by the republican [Commonwealth of England](/Commonwealth_of_England), which followed the [Wars of the Three Kingdoms](/Wars_of_the_Three_Kingdoms). Following the installation of [William III](/William_III_of_England) and [Mary II](/Mary_II) as co‑monarchs in the [Glorious Revolution](/Glorious_Revolution), the [Bill of Rights 1689](/Bill_of_Rights_1689), and its Scottish counterpart the [Claim of Right Act 1689](/Claim_of_Right_Act_1689), further curtailed the power of the monarchy and excluded [Catholics](/Catholics) from succession to the throne. In 1707, the kingdoms of England and Scotland were merged to create the [Kingdom of Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain), and in 1801, the [Kingdom of Ireland](/Kingdom_of_Ireland) joined to create the [United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland](/United_Kingdom_of_Great_Britain_and_Ireland).  

Beginning in the 16th century, the monarch was the nominal head of what came to be the vast [British Empire](/British_Empire), which covered a quarter of the world's land area at its greatest extent in 1921. The title [Emperor of India](/Emperor_of_India) was added to the British monarch's titles between 1876 and 1948. The [Balfour Declaration of 1926](/Balfour_Declaration_of_1926) recognised the evolution of the [Dominions](/Dominion) of the Empire into separate, self‑governing countries within a [Commonwealth of Nations](/Commonwealth_of_Nations). Also in this period, the monarchy in Ireland eventually became limited to [Northern Ireland](/Northern_Ireland). In the years after [World War II](/World_War_II), the vast majority of British colonies and territories became independent, effectively bringing the Empire to an end. [George VI](/George_VI) and his successors adopted the title [Head of the Commonwealth](/Head_of_the_Commonwealth) as a symbol of the free association of its independent member states. The United Kingdom and fourteen other independent sovereign states that share the same person as their monarch are called [Commonwealth realms](/Commonwealth_realm). Although the monarch is shared, each country is sovereign and independent of the others, and the monarch has a different, specific, and official national [title and style](/List_of_titles_and_honours_of_Charles_III) for each realm. Although the term is rarely used today, the fifteen Commonwealth realms are, with respect to their monarch, in [personal union](/Personal_union). The monarch is also head of state of the [Crown Dependencies](/Crown_Dependencies) and the [British Overseas Territories](/British_Overseas_Territories).  

